Previous Save Backup¶{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Garamond;}{\f1\fnil Arial;}}{&1310}{\colortbl ;\red128\green128\blue128;\red255\green255\blue255;}{&1310}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\fi720\sl480\slmult1\cf1\lang1033\f0\fs22 {&1310}\par Another awkward moment or two passed - me, just sitting there playing with my hands. I looked to Ev again, and so did Jules. Then he looked at me.{&1310}\par "Well?"{&1310}\par I shrugged. "I told you when you first landed," I grumbled back. "Right before you hit me in the face with your gun." And he just grunted.{&1310}\par "No one could've understood that mess coming out of your mouth."{&1310}\par "Ev could."{&1310}\par "What?"{&1310}\par "Nothing! Fine. Just shut up. I told you," I began again, slumping over against my knees with both hands buried back in my hair, "Ev's ship got attacked ... and her Dad is dead now. They jettisoned down here, so - I followed them."{&1310}\par "In that shuttle?"{&1310}\par I nodded my head in my hands.{&1310}\par "I kind of borrowed it from her Dad when he was done using it."{&1310}\par "I shouldn't be surprised you destroyed my ship too."{&1310}\par "\i You\i0  were the one flying it."{&1310}\par He leaned back, ignoring me for a minute or so, but staring nonetheless. Trying to read my face or something I guess. It was a little uncomfortable, and I glanced away. The wind picked up - cold. I twisted around and put my back to the cliffside again, getting as close to that fire as I dared. The Eluvian didn't move from where he was.{&1310}\par "Those pirates that attacked us," he said after a little while longer sitting in silence. "They followed your beacon like I did. I had planned on being ready for them."{&1310}\par "So you only came after us to find \i pirates\i0 ?"{&1310}\par "That's right."{&1310}\par "But - well, wha ... Where the hell is anyone who's actually coming to \i rescue \i0 us? I mean - what the fuck are those things for anyways? It's a \i distress\i0  beacon, right? And all we get are pirates ... and \i you\i0 ." I threw a hand over his way. "Somebody has to come. Right? That's how it's supposed to work!"{&1310}\par "Calm down. You'd be surprised," he told me. "But I doubt anyone would lose any sleep over a blip on their sensors around here." He glanced around. "Probably come eventually, but your friend would've been dead. You too maybe. You were lucky I happened to be in the area."{&1310}\par "Looking for pirates."{&1310}\par "That's right." he bobbed his head. "I found an old cruiser dead in the water about twenty million klicks out from here. That wouldn't've been yours, would it?"{&1310}\par "I don't know. Maybe. So you were just waiting to ambush them in our shuttle?"{&1310}\par "You've got it all figured out now, don't you?"{&1310}\par "But wouldn't they have just blasted it to pieces like they did yours?" I remembered them painting the sky with his ship well enough.{&1310}\par "No." He shook his head, though. "They would have strip-searched it for salvage first. Do as much to you too," he added a second after that first bit. "Probably worse. But the perennium is what's important."{&1310}\par I shook my head. "Why perennium?"{&1310}\par And he gave me a funny look. "Are you serious?" The demand came without nonsense. I shrugged my shoulders at him and he barked another of those humorless laughs like scraping gravel.{&1310}\par "You two must've run away from somewhere really comfortable to not have the slightest idea what I'm talking about."{&1310}\par "Maybe I do," I argued quickly. "Just start to tell me and I'll remember."{&1310}\par "I doubt it." He gave me a rough, patronizing once-over with those stone-dead eyes. Too bad. That usually worked back on Riftwatch.{&1310}\par "Perennium," he began anew, clipped and condescending. "You do know what that is, right? You're not a complete fool."{&1310}\par "What the fuck ... Yes, I know what perennium is!"{&1310}\par "Well, then you know it powers almost everything anyone ever uses. Ship drives. Life support. Weapons. Planetary atmospheric control regulators," he dripped with some sarcasm. "\i Very\i0  important."{&1310}\par "\i Yeah\i0 . I know ..."{&1310}\par "Then imagine it stopped working," he continued. "Imagine that comm on your wrist stopped working."{&1310}\par "It's dead down here anyways ..."{&1310}\par "That shuttle you crashed," he pressed on and over me irritably. "If it had lost power on entry, you would have incinerated in the atmosphere."{&1310}\par "Ooookay ..."{&1310}\par "That atmosphere - too far away from the sun to keep this little rock warm enough for you to still be breathing right now - \i melted \i0 away into space."{&1310}\par "Okay. Whatever. I get it," I cut in. "It's \i really\i0  important. What's your point?"{&1310}\par "My point is that the entire sector is in a shortage right now."{&1310}\par "So?" I shrugged. "It's not like it runs out fast or anything like that."{&1310}\par "No," he agreed with a twist of his lips. He took a long draw from his canteen. "But it has been lately."{&1310}\par "What do you mean?"{&1310}\par He shook his head. "I mean it hasn't been lasting quite as long as it should. Not long at all."{&1310}\par I looked over at him. "So, uh ... why did they just blow up your ship then," I asked, careful about how sensitive he might still be to that whole business. It's not like it was really my fault, though. {&1310}\par "You know ... instead of salvaging it."{&1310}\par "They recognized it," was all he said about that - as if it explained everything. Then he just gave a sideways glance toward Ev.{&1310}\par "Your friend is doing better."{&1310}\par "Yeah. Thanks," I mumbled back. All that talk about perennium ... I probably should have eaten something, but we had nothing left for the next day unless he was holding out on me, and my stomach felt like a sinkhole. I pawed at some water instead. Eventually, I couldn't take the quiet anymore.{&1310}\par "Where are we going?"{&1310}\par "The nearest waypoint," he said, as if that should have meant anything to me. "A town or city. They should have a transit rail to whatever spaceport still exists on this moon." He took his canteen and filled it from the stores in his pack from the ship. It was almost gone too.{&1310}\par "Moon?" I asked.{&1310}\par "Yeah," he admitted, glancing around to the treetops above - black now with the night, and blocking out the stars above. "The daylight doesn't seem odd to you? No, it wouldn't, would it."{&1310}\par "Odd?" I quirked an eyebrow at him, glancing up and trying to remember. "What's wrong with it? That's how it supposed to look, right?"{&1310}\par "It's completely artificial. Look," he pointed up above, and I followed him. "Stars. I think we'll be planetward tomorrow. It's a little far off, but you might be able to see it."{&1310}\par "See what?"{&1310}\par He gave me another frustrated, impatient look. "The planet. Dreggoran."{&1310}\par "Oh. Really?"{&1310}\par "Unless we already passed it."{&1310}\par I hadn't even noticed those first couple days. Maybe there was something in the clouds, washed away in the sky? It seemed such a shame to miss. People always said that the Rift was beautiful to come see, but I wondered what an entire planet would look like up in that sky. Probably a lot more so.{&1310}\par "What did you mean - completely artificial?" I asked after a couple more seconds of just staring up.{&1310}\par "Just like the atmosphere." He raised a finger up, resting the elbow on his knee. "All just to make this ... rock ... liveable."{&1310}\par "Wow."{&1310}\par It was hard to think about. I mean, sure we had some pretty fancy things back on Riftwatch, but ... terraforming an entire planet? I guess that explained why any of those smaller moons were habitable, if you thought about it. But I'd never read or seen anything much about the whole thing. {&1310}\par I came back down, opening my mouth to ask who could've possibly built something like that. I never got that far, though. {&1310}\par I turned my head around to look at him again, but something caught my eye instead. My mouth was still open as I froze, staring off that way. And I blinked. There was a black shape against the trees, a dozen meters away outside the firelight.{&1310}\par "What ..." I started, but never finished.{&1310}\par Jules glanced over at me, instantly following my eyes out into the woods. His hands flew towards his rifle so fast, I didn't even register it until he had the thing up and pointed that way. He twisted something on the barrel, and a beam of light flushed out the dark.{&1310}\par There was a glimpse. Something black, and smooth between ribbed folds. That's all I could see for a split-second before it stepped back out of the light behind the trees.{&1310}\par I think I screamed.\cf2\f1 {&1310}\par }{&1310}
